<HEAD>Pyramid Billed As Memphis' Future Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A giant groundbreaking party, ``The Big
Dig,'' is set for the Great American Pyramid sports and
entertainment arena, which is being touted as a prime tourist
attraction when it opens in <DATE>1991</DATE>.
   ``It's the first pyramid of consequence to be built in 5,000
years and it just happens to have an arena in it,'' said <PERSON>Sidney
Shlenker</PERSON>, who helped develop <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>'s Astrodome in the <DATE>1960s</DATE> and is
working on the pyramid.
   Groundbreaking is scheduled for <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, complete with
parades, street parties and fireworks. It will feature a
75-foot-long arrangement of lights in the shape of a shovel, and a
light and laser display showing the size of the future pyramid.
   That display will be formed by stringing lights from a
321-foot-tall industrial crane at the center of the pyramid site,
said <PERSON>Henry Turley Jr.</PERSON>, a <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION> real estate developer helping
organize the groundbreaking, called ``The Big Dig.''
   With music traditional to <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION> playing over loudspeakers along
the downtown riverfront, a police helicopter will deliver the
75-foot ``shovel'' to signal the beginning of a fireworks display,
<PERSON>Turley</PERSON> said.
   Comedian <PERSON>Dan Aykroyd</PERSON> will perform at the <LOCATION>Mud Island</LOCATION> party with
other members of the <ORGANIZATION>Blues Brother</ORGANIZATION> review, a rock 'n' roll band
featured in a movie by the same name starring <PERSON>Aykroyd</PERSON> and the late
<PERSON>John Belushi</PERSON>.
   Local government is paying for the <MONEY>$56 million</MONEY> arena. <PERSON>Shlenker</PERSON>
has an agreement to operate it, take the lion's share of any profits
and pay the money back over 25 years.
   He also has a contract giving him control of a nearby <MONEY>$63 million</MONEY>
tourist park the city built in <DATE>1983</DATE> on a 3-mile-long <LOCATION>Mississippi
River</LOCATION> sandbar called <LOCATION>Mud Island</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Shlenker</PERSON>, a former owner of the <ORGANIZATION>Denver Nuggets of the National
Basketball Association</ORGANIZATION>, runs four <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION> corporations, which he
groups under the name of <ORGANIZATION>The Pyramid Companies</ORGANIZATION>. He and his principal
financial partner, international businessman <PERSON>John Tigrett Sr.</PERSON>,
expect to spend some <MONEY>$80 million</MONEY> developing the pyramid-park project.
   The pyramid began with plans four years ago to provide a new
basketball arena for <ORGANIZATION>Memphis State University</ORGANIZATION>. The idea grew of
building a pyramid-shaped arena to play on <LOCATION>Memphis</LOCATION>' link to its
namesake, the ancient capital of <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION> which stood beside the <ORGANIZATION>Nile</ORGANIZATION>.
  
</TEXT>
